  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Here's a breakdown of the key ones:\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988 Vienna Convention):** This was one of the first major international agreements to address money laundering. It focused primarily on drug-related money laundering and required countries to criminalize the laundering of proceeds from drug trafficking and to cooperate in international investigations.\n\n*   **United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000 Palermo Convention):** This convention broadened the scope of money laundering offenses beyond drug trafficking to include the laundering of proceeds from a wide range of serious crimes, including organized crime, corruption, and terrorism financing. It also promoted international cooperation in asset recovery.\n\n*   **International Convention for the Suppression of the Financing of Terrorism (1999):** While not exclusively focused on money laundering, this convention plays a crucial role in combating money laundering related to terrorism",
